^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, as to responsive doubles. A responsive double works as follows. First of all, to make a responsive double, your partner has to be an overcaller, either with a takeout double or a suit. In the simplest case the bidding goes 1x-dbl or overcall-2x-dbl. For example the double in the following auction|HT|J|at|^B{|ia|1s2h2sd|at|}|HT|k|AT|^mis a responsive double, and shows the remaining unbid suits. |
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


HT|n|AT|^B{|ia|1sd2sr|at|}|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


HT|o|AT|^n and|HT|N|AT|^p{|ia|1d1h2dd|at|}|HT|r|AT|
^B@2are additional examples of responsive doubles.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


at| It is simple to distinguish between a responsive double and a negative double. A negative double is made after an opening bid followed by an overcall such as|HT|u|AT|^b{|ia|1c1sd|at|}|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


HT|t|at|^m@2^Z@3Therefore, a negative double is made by responder to an opening bid. A responsive double is made by the partner of an overcaller. So, a negative double is the third bid in the auction, a responsive double the 4th bid. |
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


