BT||QX||HT|e|cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|To make my instructions better understood, let me recap the last hand. Once K bids, he is showing 6-9, with 3 hearts. So, if D has at least 16, there is some chance that the side has game, if K is on the top of his range (8 or 9). If D has 16 or 17, she should try for game. If she has 18 or more, she should just bid game. |
PG| ***** 167 ***** |


AT|

With unbalanced hand, she could bid 3@H with 16 or 17 (asking K to bid 4@H with 8 or 9) or make a help suit game try. With an unbalanced 18+ point hand, she  should just bid game. With a balanced hand, she could ask K to choose between NT and hearts, because sometimes NT is easier, as 3NT requires one less trick than 4@H. |
PG| ***** 168 ***** |


AT|

If K had a balanced hand as well, he therefore might choose NT rather than hearts. So with a game forcing balanced hand (18+) D could bid 3NT, giving K a choice between 3NT and 4@H. With an invitational balanced hand (16 or 17), she could bid 2NT, giving him both a choice of strain (NT or hearts), and a choice of level (either a partial or game). In other words, if she bids 2NT, K's possible responses are pass with a balanced 6 or 7, 3@H with an unbalanced 6 or 7, 3NT with a balanced 8 or 9, or 4@H with an unbalanced 8 or 9.  |
PG| ***** 169 ***** |


AT|

I would have passed 2NT with K's hand, since he also has a balanced hand with less than 8. But if I had D's hand, I would have bid 3NT, and K again should pass because his hand is balanced.  |
